deck: Sometimes the long arm of the law needs help in extending its reach.
description:
Origin

Craig Mansfield was a private eye who along with the prerequisite skills of toughness and snooping had an unusual surprise edge. He was a little person who was seen by the rest of the world as an average sized man through the use of specially built “racks” that he wore on his legs to not only add his height but via the use of a button on his wrist retract and extend them so he could shoot up to as tall as nine feet tall, or when setting down fire them like a weapon.

Creators

One of a number of short lived backup features in Airboy Comics, in this case in the first story drawn by Fred Gaurdineer and scripted by an unknown writer, each Rackman story opened with this.

“Rackman: On a lonely island along the Atlantic coast lives the fabulously wealthy Mansfield family. They are dwarfs who give themselves added height by the use of ingenious racks… and their guarded secrecy is only disturbed by the knowledge that their son, Craig, has chosen to move among less fortunate people as a crusader against crime and injustice.”

Craig’s son returned as Rackman in the 80’s in the revival of Airboy.
name: Rackman

deck: God of Love, and potential paramour of Amora.
description:
Major Story Arcs

Desperate for a real romantic relationship after so many empty affairs, Amora the Enchantress falls in love with Love itself. She created a physical body for him and romanced him.

However she felt that she was not worthy of him, and needed the Rose of Purity to bring herself back to a state of purity. She couldn't get it herself so she blackmailed the Defenders into going after it.

However, after realizing that the Rose was a sentient god itself, the Defenders refused. Love was also unhappy with Amora's machinations, and refused to stay as her lover. He telepathically contacted a different group of Defenders to come and stop Amora. Then, as a means of recompense for the evil she had done, he took the insane soul of Barbara Norriss, which the Enchantress had imprisoned in the body of Valkyrie, and brought Norriss back to sanity. Then he brought her into his own ethereal sphere to live with as his lover forever, since her own body had been destroyed, thereby fully spurning Amora. (Eventually Norriss returned to Earth.)

It is unclear whether Love is an Asgardian god, or from some other pantheon, or is a force of the universe outside the Earthly pantheons. He never had a physical form until Amora created for him. It should be noted that in his first on-panel appearance, he looked quite a bit like cliche Western images of Christ, standing around peacefully in white robes and long auburn hair with a bunch of animals; J.M. DeMatteis's run on Defenders often used such cultural and literary references and tropes.
name: Love
